    <name>SAMPLE: Practice: Now you try it</name>
    <intro>&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;{&lt;em&gt;This is a &lt;strong&gt;sample only&lt;/strong&gt;. Do not complete it. It is for review purposes only.&lt;/em&gt;}&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;It's time to recreate a portion of the video to determine just how simple some of these ideas really were.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;Use the data identified in the video to calculate the circumference of the earth based upon the equations identified by Eratosthenes 2,200 years ago. &lt;em&gt;Do not forget to show your work&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;To save you the trouble of going back and watching the video again to find your measurements and equations they have been provided below:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul style="text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Angle of a sphere = 360° (Aristotle concluded that the earth was a sphere due to his observations.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Sun's shadow in Swenet is directly overhead at noon on the sun's solstice.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Sun's shadow in Alexandria on the solstice is 7.2° off-axis at noon.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Distance between the city of Swenet and Alexandria = 500 miles.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;Using that data, you should be able to determine (within 1%) the circumference of the earth.&lt;/p&gt;</intro>
